    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA288-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi (ET: talaivaṉ) ciṟaippuṟamākat (ET: tōḻi) talaimakaṭku uraippāḷāy veṟi aṟivuṟīi varaivu kaṭāyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante urged for marriage by announcing the Veṟi [dance] as one who is talking to HER when [HE] was behind the fence.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA288">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            aruvi yārkku maṇaṅkuṭai neṭuṅkōṭṭu</l>
<l>            ñāṅka riḷaveyi luṇīiya vōṅkuciṉaip</l>
<l>            pīli maññai peṭaiyō ṭāṭuṅ</l>
<l>            kuṉṟa nāṭaṉ piriviṟ ceṉṟu</l>
<l>            naṉṉutaṟ paranta pacalaikaṇ ṭaṉṉai </l>
<l>            cemmutu peṇṭiroṭu neṉmuṉ ṉiṟīik</l>
<l>            kaṭṭiṟ kēṭku māyiṉ veṟpi</l>
<l>            lēṉaṟ centiṉaip pālār koḻuṅkuraṟ</l>
<l>            ciṟukiḷi kaṭikañ ceṉṟumin</l>
<l>            neṭuvē ḷaṇaṅkiṟ ṟeṉṉuṅko latuvē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">Since mother hesitates in front of the rice-grains,<note place="foot">Here T.V.G. explains a technique that reminds us curiously of the North-Indian dice game: the women would take a fistful of rice and count it by four up to the end, and the number of the remaining corns tells the reason for the disease. Is there a rest of one, two or three corns, the culprit is <term xml:lang="ta">Murukaṉ</term>; is nothing left, it may have another cause.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">together with upright old women,</l>
<l rend="indent">having seen<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaṇṭaṉṉai</term>: here we can ask whether we rather have to dissolve, with the special sandhi, as <term xml:lang="ta">kaṇṭa aṉṉai</term>, which would be the form to be expected here, but on the other hand this poem plays with a very loose application of absolutives.</note> pallor spread on [my] good forehead</l>
<l rend="indent2">after he had gone into separation, the man from the hilly land,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where the fan[-tailed] peacock is dancing with [its] female</l>
<l rend="indent3">on a high branch, enjoying the young sunlight above</l>
<l rend="indent3">on the long awe-inspiring peak where the waterfall sounds,</l>
<l rend="indent3">– when we’ll hear the divination,</l>
<l rend="indent3">though we [just] chased away the little parrots</l>
<l rend="indent3">from the milky rich ears of the red millet on the mountain,</l>
<l>will it say “that [is] a torment [sent by] this great Murukaṉ”?</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
